SIMPLE: purl
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Purl
<hw>Purl</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Contr. fr.
<ets>purfile</ets>, <ets>purfle</ets>. See <er>Purfle</er>.]</ety>
<def>To decorate with fringe or embroidery.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Nature's cradle
more enchased and <xex>purled</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>B.
Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Purl</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Purl
<hw>Purl</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An embroidered and
puckered border; a hem or fringe, often of gold or silver twist; also, a
pleat or fold, as of a band.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A triumphant chariot made of carnation velvet, enriched
with<qex>purl</qex> and pearl.</q> <rj><qau>Sir P.
Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An inversion of stitches in knitting, which gives to
the work a ribbed or waved appearance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Purl stitch</b></col>. <cd>Same as <er>Purl</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, 2.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Purl</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Purl
<hw>Purl</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Purled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Purling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. Sw. <ets>porla</ets>, and E.
<ets>pur</ets> to murmur as a cat.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To run
swiftly round, as a small stream flowing among stones or other
obstructions; to eddy; also, to make a murmuring sound, as water does in
running over or through obstructions.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Swift o'er the rolling pebbles, down the hills,⟦br⟧
Louder and louder <qex>purl</qex> the falling rills.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[Perh. fr. F. <ets>perler</ets> to pearl, to bead.
See <er>Pearl</er>, <pos>v. & n.</pos>]</ety> <def>To rise in circles,
ripples, or undulations; to curl; to mantle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>thin winding breath which <qex>purled</qex> up to the sky.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Purl</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Purl
<hw>Purl</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See 3d <er>Purl</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A circle made by the notion of a fluid; an eddy; a
ripple.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whose stream an easy breath doth seem to blow,⟦br⟧
Which on the sparkling gravel runs in <qex>purles</qex>,⟦br⟧
As though the waves had been of silver curls.</q>
<rj><qau>Drayton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A gentle murmur, as that produced by the running of
a liquid among obstructions; <as>as, the <ex>purl</ex> of a
brook</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <ety>[Perh. from F. <ets>perler</ets>, v. See
<er>Purl</er> to mantle.]</ety> <def>Malt liquor, medicated or spiced;
formerly, ale or beer in which wormwood or other bitter herbs had been
infused, and which was regarded as tonic; at present, hot beer mixed
with gin, sugar, and spices.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Drank a glass of
<xex>purl</xex> to recover appetite.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Addison.</au>
⟦ldquo⟧Drinking hot <xex>purl</xex>, and smoking pipes.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Dickens.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A tern.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Purlieu</ent>⟦br⟧
